[3] Cholera - Iraq (northern)
Date: Wed 12 Sep 2007
Source: International Herald Tribune, Associated Press report [edited]
<http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2007/09/12/africa/ME-GEN-Iraq-Cholera.php>

The cholera outbreak in northern Iraq has so far been limited to 3
provinces but could spread south, though countermeasures are being
taken, a Health Ministry official said Wed 12 Sep 2007.
Since the disease broke out in mid-August 2007, 10 people have died
and some 700 others have been confirmed with cholera, said Adel
Muhsin, the Health Ministry's inspector general. Another 11 000 are
suffering from symptoms like severe diarrhea and vomiting, Muhsin said.
Worst hit has been the city of Sulaimaniyah, in the province of the
same name, which has seen 4600 cases of diarrhea and 300 cases of
cholera, said Sherko Abdullah, the head of the regional health
ministry department. Of the 10 deaths, 9 have been in the city, he
said. It has also been reported in the northern provinces of Erbil
[spelled Arbil on the map below - Mod.LL] and Tamim [At Ta'mim on the
map, also known as Kirkuk province. - Mod.LL]
"No new cases have been discovered yet in other parts in Iraq and it
is not impossible this will happen, but we are taking steps to
contain and prevent the disease from spreading to other areas," Muhsin said.
Last week [3-9 Sep 2007], United Nations Development Program (UNDP)
official Paolo Lembo said the outbreak was caused by the "inadequacy
of the water supply system and deteriorated infrastructure" of the
area. Now, medical teams are regularly testing drinking water in
Baghdad and other areas, and the Health Ministry is working to
provide chlorine to drinking water plants, which can kill the
bacteria responsible for cholera.
"The more we pay attention to the drinking water regarding chlorine,
the more we prevent an outbreak of this disease elsewhere," Muhsin said.
--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[The numbers of estimated cases of diarrhea are increased, but how
much of these numbers are cholera is unclear. The affected provinces
can be found on a map at
<http://www.un.org/Depts/Cartographic/map/profile/iraq.pdf>. Given
the overall state of the infrastructure of Iraq further spread to
more central areas of the country is certainly possible. - Mod.LL]
